WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
You know that feeling you get when you've got these really good results and you're just

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:15.680
really excited to share them with the world, and you think everyone's going to be really

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.799
excited to see what results you have?

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:23.959
And then you know that other feeling you sometimes get with that one, when you get this sinking

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:28.680
suspicion that maybe those really good results are just too good to be true?

00:00:29.559 --> 00:00:32.279
So this happened to me a few months ago.

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:34.520
I lead the engineering team at Ursa Labs.

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:39.480
We're one of the leading developers behind the Apache Arrow project.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:44.599
So Arrow, as you may know, is essentially building the foundation for the next generation

00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:47.599
of data frames and bigger data analysis.

00:00:47.599 --> 00:00:50.240
And I maintain Arrow's R package.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:55.080
So I was meeting with RStudio's leadership, because RStudio has been a generous sponsor

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.720
of Ursa Labs from the beginning.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:06.400
So I'm in the call, and I'm there with Hadley Wickham, and with JJ Allaire, founder, CEO

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.239
of RStudio, Tarif Khalaf, who's president.

00:01:09.239 --> 00:01:13.919
And I was talking about this result that I found recently, which was I'd been benchmarking

00:01:13.919 --> 00:01:19.160
Arrow's CSV reader, and found that Arrow has lots of great things that it does in its library.

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:21.440
I'm going to show you some of them in this talk.

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:26.599
But even if you just use Arrow as a CSV reader, and use it to read a data frame into R, and

00:01:26.599 --> 00:01:30.400
then you could use any other R package on that data frame afterwards, you could get

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:31.400
a big benefit.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:36.839
And in fact, even on this particular New York City taxi data set that I was testing out

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:43.519
on, I found that Arrow was two to three times faster than DataTable's CSV reader.

00:01:43.519 --> 00:01:48.599
And at this point, Hadley cuts me off and says, yeah, I don't know, that doesn't sound

00:01:48.599 --> 00:01:49.599
right.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:55.559
But DataTable, that group, they have optimized really everything that you could optimize

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:58.639
out of reading data into R.

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:03.080
And so maybe you could match their performance.

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:04.080
Maybe you could get a little bit better.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:07.559
But you couldn't be that much better, because they've done everything you could do.

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:11.279
And Tarif added, yeah, you probably screwed up something in your benchmarking code.

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:15.600
You probably actually didn't do all the work you thought you did.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:19.479
And I thought about it, and it's like, wow, that's actually a much more logical, simpler

00:02:19.479 --> 00:02:23.559
explanation for the result that I found, that I screwed up something in my code.

00:02:23.559 --> 00:02:28.479
But I figured I'd go check it out and get back to them.

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:31.160
And I compared the objects that I had.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:36.080
The data frames read by both were the same size, 15 million rows, both really big in

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:37.080
memory.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:38.080
So it checked out.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:44.000
It turned out Arrow's CSV reader was two to three times faster than DataTable's here.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.720
So we'd achieved an incredible result.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:48.580
It was literally incredible.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:52.960
This group of people here that know a lot about the internals of R literally did not

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.679
believe that it was this fast.

00:02:55.679 --> 00:02:58.479
So how were we able to do that?

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:04.960
So what I want to talk about today is how characteristics of the Arrow project, and

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:10.240
particularly the community around it, enable us to do things that we might otherwise have

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:15.119
thought would be impossible to do in R.

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:17.199
So a little history.

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:20.800
So Arrow was started in 2016.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:27.000
A group of database developers and data frame library maintainers got together and realized

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.279
that they were all trying to solve similar problems.

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:34.399
And rather than saying, this is fine, and we're just going to keep duplicating each

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:39.880
other's work, what if we work together and create a shared foundation for our work?

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:42.759
And we would all benefit from that.

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:45.679
So Arrow is fundamentally about three things.

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:51.839
First is it is a format, is a specification for how data is represented in memory.

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:57.960
It's columnar, and it's designed to take advantage of features of modern CPUs and GPUs and other

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:00.559
hardware.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:05.160
There's also a set of 12 libraries that implement it in different languages.

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.919
Python and R use the C++ library.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:14.440
But there are many others in the Arrow project.

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:20.480
And then third, there's this broader ecosystem of packages and projects around Arrow that

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:25.500
use Arrow in some form, whether it's as their internal data model, or is it just a means

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.760
of exchange between projects.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:36.600
So how do these characteristics of Arrow lead us to get such unbelievable performance and

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:42.000
be able to enable us to do things that we didn't think were possible in R?

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.720
So in terms of modern hardware, Arrow is designed to take advantage of many features of CPUs

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:52.519
that exist now that didn't exist when R was developed initially.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:56.000
So R was first released in 1995.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.920
Of course, computer technology has progressed quite a bit since then.

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:05.079
And there's things that I can do on my laptop now that was not something that was a thing

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:06.679
back then.

00:05:06.679 --> 00:05:11.000
So for example, my laptop here has got eight cores.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.279
That's CPUs that you can run in parallel.

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:17.359
You can get a host on AWS with 96 cores.

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:18.679
That's pretty good.

00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:20.880
But R is generally only using one of those.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:24.600
So we're leaving a lot of performance on the table.

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:30.239
Newer CPUs also can take advantage of what's called SIMD, single instruction multiple data.

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:33.839
My laptop, for example, can take up to 256 bits at a time.

00:05:33.839 --> 00:05:39.279
So that would be the size of eight integers in R. Other newer ones can do 512 bits.

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:44.760
So you can feed a lot more data into the CPU at a time if your code is designed to take

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:48.480
advantage of that, but R generally is not.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:53.760
So it's like you have this super fast sports car and you just want to take it for a spin

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.760
around the track and see what you can do with it.

00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:04.440
But for whatever reason, you have to keep it under 25 miles an hour, drive, keep your

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:09.519
hands at 10 and 2 on the steering wheel, nothing too crazy.

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:11.880
And it's a really missed opportunity.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:12.799
So what do you do about that?

00:06:12.799 --> 00:06:20.480
So you could write some C or C++ code in your R package to do multi-threading to take advantage

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.839
of all those extra cores that you have available.

00:06:23.839 --> 00:06:31.200
You could write code to do SIMD optimizations, but that's really hard, frankly.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:37.440
And the number of people that know how to do that well isn't that great, probably.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:44.079
And the number of people who do that and are going to be writing R packages is even smaller.

00:06:44.079 --> 00:06:48.359
So here's where the large Arrow community comes in handy here.

00:06:48.359 --> 00:06:56.480
So the Arrow project, since it was created in 2016, has had a steady growth of contributors

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:01.440
to the project over time, well over 500 by now.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:06.239
And what this means is all of these people are working together on this project and the

00:07:06.239 --> 00:07:07.839
benefits are shared.

00:07:07.839 --> 00:07:14.880
So in order to have smart multi-threading in the R package, I didn't have to write that.

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:18.519
Anyone else who understands how to do that much better than I would did that.

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:20.839
I didn't have to write SIMD code either.

00:07:20.839 --> 00:07:26.399
There are other people, people who work on hardware that's the actual CPUs themselves

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:29.079
that know what those options are.

00:07:29.079 --> 00:07:30.720
They wrote that code.

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:31.720
And they're all contributing it in.

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:36.079
And they're not contributing it in because they want to make the R package faster.

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:41.760
They're contributing it in because they are using the C++ library for some other project

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:46.359
or they're using Python, which uses the same C++ library that the R package does.

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:52.000
So we benefit from all these other communities' contributions.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.200
So what does that look like?

00:07:54.200 --> 00:08:00.200
So to give an example of how this work plays out in reality, I want to talk about this

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:04.720
example, this demo that I gave last year at RStudio conference.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:11.720
I was introducing the Arrow R package and I was going through this example with the

00:08:11.720 --> 00:08:20.399
data set where you take about 10.5 years of New York City taxi data, 2 billion rows, and

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:24.679
you could scan that and get some results on that on your laptop.

00:08:24.679 --> 00:08:30.839
So I did some kind of sample dplyr, filtering and selecting and grouping and aggregating

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.320
on this data set that I'd opened with the Arrow package where I pointed at a directory

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:38.239
of these files and then I could query it.

00:08:38.239 --> 00:08:41.479
And I got a result in four seconds over 2 billion rows.

00:08:41.479 --> 00:08:42.479
That was pretty good.

00:08:42.479 --> 00:08:44.760
We're really happy with that.

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:49.960
I did a talk this past summer and I redid the result just on the latest version of the

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.799
code and it was twice as fast.

00:08:52.799 --> 00:08:55.919
And I hadn't really done anything in the R package to do that.

00:08:55.919 --> 00:09:00.760
This is all based on improvements in the underlying C++ code that all the rest of the community

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:03.239
was working on.

00:09:03.239 --> 00:09:07.840
Right before I did this talk now, I ran the code again on the latest version and it's

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:09.840
another 25% faster.

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:13.599
Again, I didn't do anything to make that happen.

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:18.159
It's just based on the Arrow community and its work.

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:24.719
So there's other reasons, other ways that this ecosystem plays out and has benefits

00:09:24.719 --> 00:09:28.960
for us in our community.

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:34.119
So when you hear that a bunch of database developers got together and decided that there

00:09:34.119 --> 00:09:40.239
wasn't a good standard for columnar data and they were going to create their own standard

00:09:40.239 --> 00:09:48.039
to unify all of these, it might bring this XKCD comic to mind where the creation of standards

00:09:48.039 --> 00:09:53.919
to solve the lack of standards just makes more problems, more standards, more competing

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:54.919
standards.

00:09:54.919 --> 00:09:56.960
And there certainly is that risk.

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:04.799
But five years on from the creation of Arrow, we can see now how the benefits of this approach

00:10:04.799 --> 00:10:07.000
have played out.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:15.039
So just to give an example, so suppose I've got data in Spark and I want really quick

00:10:15.039 --> 00:10:21.520
access to that in Python and R. What you could do is that you could from Spark, you could

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:30.280
write a special adapter for Python, a special adapter for R that understands, in R's case,

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:37.239
you understand R's vector types and specific, the bits in the vectors that make up a data

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:38.239
frame.

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:43.599
And you have to do the same thing for Python, for NumPy or Pandas.

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:48.280
And Spark and its Java code would have to understand how to do this.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:52.640
I put another arrow in the chart there to connect the interchange between Python and R.

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:54.840
That's obviously something you'd want to do too.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:58.840
And it's another place where you'd need someone on the other side of the language barrier

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:02.520
to understand the internals of your format.

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.440
So that's feasible if this is all you care about.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:09.880
But in reality, the system is, there's many more languages and there's many more projects

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:13.559
and too many to fit on the slide.

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:17.719
And as you can imagine, if you try to draw all of those lines to connect the various

00:11:17.719 --> 00:11:21.960
adapters to the different things, it gets crazy really quickly.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:22.960
So what do you do?

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:24.599
You're obviously not going to do that.

00:11:24.599 --> 00:11:27.000
That's too much work.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.840
And so what you want is to have a ubiquitous standard that everyone can write to and read

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:39.760
from and then you don't have to re-implement everything every time.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:46.719
So prior to Arrow, what you do is probably just dump out a CSV.

00:11:46.719 --> 00:11:48.479
Every language knows how to read a CSV.

00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:51.960
Every database knows how to read in a CSV.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.159
But this comes with some costs.

00:11:54.159 --> 00:12:00.479
CSVs can be expensive to read and write because you have to convert between a string format

00:12:00.479 --> 00:12:10.479
on disk to the arrays of bits that R and other languages use in memory to do work.

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:12.400
And that conversion is costly.

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:15.359
And CSV also doesn't have rich support for types.

00:12:15.359 --> 00:12:20.359
You may have timestamps and you don't have any way of indicating that this is a timestamp.

00:12:20.359 --> 00:12:24.400
You have to guess whether it should be just a regular string or a timestamp.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:28.239
And so there's lots of costs and penalties that come from doing this.

00:12:28.239 --> 00:12:33.080
But CSV is kind of the lowest common denominator and so that's why it gets picked up.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:40.280
But Arrow is kind of a happier version of that where you have a standard and it's columnar

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:41.400
and it's binary.

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:48.280
So it matches very closely with how R or Julia or Spark or any of these languages actually

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:50.520
work with data in memory.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:56.919
So the conversion is minimal and in some cases doesn't actually involve copying memory because

00:12:56.919 --> 00:13:00.299
it where it does actually line up as being the same shape.

00:13:00.299 --> 00:13:02.479
So it's very efficient.

00:13:02.479 --> 00:13:07.159
And from our perspective in the R community, what this means is once we have and now that

00:13:07.159 --> 00:13:13.200
we have an Arrow R package, we have access to all of these other projects and databases

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:19.000
and languages very efficiently as long as they also can write to Arrow.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.919
And over the last five years, we've seen an increasing number of projects that have picked

00:13:22.919 --> 00:13:26.760
up on Arrow for this because it's really efficient.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:36.119
So going back to Spark for our example there, early on in Arrow's life, we added support

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:44.000
in PySpark, the Python Spark library, to communicate with Spark the database which is written in

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.239
Java very efficiently using Arrow.

00:13:47.239 --> 00:13:53.679
And so you'd get a hundredfold speed up on certain operations whether it's with user

00:13:53.679 --> 00:13:59.719
defined functions or whether you're just pulling a large amount of data into your Python environment

00:13:59.719 --> 00:14:02.780
to do further analysis on it.

00:14:02.780 --> 00:14:07.419
And that worked because Java has an Arrow library, Python has an Arrow library, and

00:14:07.419 --> 00:14:09.500
they write the same format.

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:14.940
The beauty of this is that once we finally got the R package going, we could pick up

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:16.380
and do the same thing.

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:19.979
These are both references to blog posts on the Arrow website.

00:14:19.979 --> 00:14:23.380
So we were able to take advantage of the same thing.

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:29.820
And because we can read and write Arrow from R, we didn't need to do any other special

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:38.820
Spark business in order to get those 100x speed ups of pulling data to and from Spark

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:39.820
in R.

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:47.539
So, the Arrow format is designed to take advantage of modern hardware and the power of the large

00:14:47.539 --> 00:14:53.500
community of developers around the Arrow project really changed what we're able to do in R

00:14:53.500 --> 00:15:00.619
and enable all sorts of new workflows that weren't really possible or feasible before.

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:09.340
So it's nice, like I showed in the beginning, to see that Arrow makes reading CSVs into

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:16.859
R faster, and we like seeing that, but that's really not the goal.

00:15:16.859 --> 00:15:21.900
We're not just trying to shave off a little bit of time from work that you already can

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:23.099
do now.

00:15:23.099 --> 00:15:25.580
We're trying to go beyond that.

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:29.979
We're trying to enable new workflows that were either cost prohibitive to do before

00:15:29.979 --> 00:15:33.380
or just, frankly, not possible at all.

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:39.539
So there's a lot more coming in the coming releases this year in 2021.

00:15:39.539 --> 00:15:44.179
I'm really excited to be able to tell you about them when they come, but for now I wanted

00:15:44.179 --> 00:15:49.059
to just go back and walk you through another example of something you can do today in the

00:15:49.059 --> 00:15:56.900
Arrow package that is a little bit beyond what you would normally do in R but can really

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:01.619
have some impossible seeming results, let's say.

00:16:01.619 --> 00:16:10.460
So earlier I showed reading a dataset of 125 files of New York City taxi data that was

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:13.539
in the parquet format.

00:16:13.539 --> 00:16:17.719
Parquet is a file format that you can read in the Arrow package.

00:16:17.719 --> 00:16:21.159
It's a columnar, very efficient file format.

00:16:21.159 --> 00:16:24.479
Often of course you don't have parquet files yet, and one of the reasons you want to use

00:16:24.479 --> 00:16:29.559
Arrow is to get your less efficient CSV data into parquet so that you can read it more

00:16:29.559 --> 00:16:31.520
quickly.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:35.520
So the Arrow package has some facilities for doing this.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:36.520
So here's an example.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:40.400
I read, I converted some of those parquet files back to CSV.

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:46.119
I only did six months of it because CSVs are big and it takes a lot of space.

00:16:46.119 --> 00:16:51.000
So you can, just as you can point at a directory of parquet files and say open dataset, you

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:58.400
can do that with CSVs and you can do the same kinds of queries on them that you did, I showed

00:16:58.400 --> 00:17:04.319
with the parquet dataset, selecting and filtering and grouping, aggregating all of these things.

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:08.439
As you see, the result here, the one I showed, it's a different query so it's not apples

00:17:08.439 --> 00:17:14.959
to apples, but it took seven and a half seconds to do this query over this data.

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:15.959
It's pretty good.

00:17:15.959 --> 00:17:20.199
In fact, I didn't have to mess with reading each of the files individually and doing things

00:17:20.199 --> 00:17:21.199
with it.

00:17:21.199 --> 00:17:22.199
That's good.

00:17:22.199 --> 00:17:25.760
But, you know, I think we can do better.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:30.040
So one of the things we want to do is we could write the dataset to a more efficient format,

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:33.719
either parquet, as I mentioned, or feather, which is the Arrow format.

00:17:33.719 --> 00:17:37.680
It's literally the Arrow format on disk.

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:43.719
So we can use similar types of dplyr style syntax to do this.

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:48.119
I can say group by this payment type column in the dataset.

00:17:48.119 --> 00:17:51.800
That was one of the columns that I filtered on before.

00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:55.839
In this case, when I'm writing a dataset, when I say group by, what that means is I

00:17:55.839 --> 00:17:59.239
want you to partition my data by that.

00:17:59.239 --> 00:18:04.319
And what that's going to do is it's going to write out separate files inside different

00:18:04.319 --> 00:18:07.800
directories based on the value of that variable.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:11.520
So payment type in this dataset took on values one to five.

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:16.760
So now I've got inside my feather taxi directory, I've got five subdirectories, one for each

00:18:16.760 --> 00:18:23.160
of the values of payment type, that now have different parquet files in it, or feather

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:24.160
files.

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:25.160
Excuse me.

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:32.359
And what this means is when I do a query again on this dataset, and if I filter on payment

00:18:32.359 --> 00:18:37.800
type, I only have to look at the files inside that directory that correspond to the value

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:39.439
of payment type that I'm filtering on.

00:18:39.439 --> 00:18:43.640
I don't even have to read the other files in to see if they match my filter, because

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:47.640
I've kind of pre-filtered it based on this partitioning.

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:52.160
So indeed, if we do the same query that I just did on the CSVs, but I do it on the feather

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:56.640
version of the dataset, it's now a hundred times faster than before.

00:18:56.640 --> 00:19:04.760
Exact same query, just with a more efficient file format, and taking advantage of partitioning

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:06.839
in the dataset query.

00:19:06.839 --> 00:19:09.079
So this is great.

00:19:09.079 --> 00:19:13.760
We're trying to make things that have been difficult or impossible, possible.

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:19.479
Trying to help you take full advantage of the sports car that you've got on your lap

00:19:19.479 --> 00:19:27.359
when you're working in R. But really, I like to think what we have is not just any old

00:19:27.359 --> 00:19:32.640
sports car, but it's a DeLorean, perhaps with a flex capacitor in it.

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:35.160
And where we're going, we don't need roads.

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:40.920
We're going beyond what you could be doing on your laptop today, even.

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:42.280
So thank you very much.

